	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>The Caribbean is concerned over lack of movement on restructuring support</h1>

			
			<h4>
												12 July 2005
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> Addressing the second meeting of sugar stakeholders on May 10th 2005 in Georgetown, Guyana, Guyana's minister of foreign trade and international cooperation, Clement Rohee, expressed concern at the WTO appellate body ruling, maintaining that CARICOM's concerns had been 'ignored'. He further noted that CARICOM's request for the EC to establish a 'competitiveness fund' had so far fallen on deaf ears, with, according to press reports, the EC refusing support to some 15 sugar projects which had been put forward. He called for Trade Commissioner Mandelson to be held to 'his promise for an early EU assistance package to the region to reduce the impact of the new sugar regime'. Minister Rohee added 'I believe the time has come to end the shadow boxing with the Commission. We must engage frontally with the Trade, Development, and Agriculture Commissioners, since they have themselves expressed a desire to discuss these matters with us'.</p><p> Meanwhile in Tanzania, press reports indicate that EU experts are already at work 'to identify areas requiring assistance in raising efficiency in Tanzania's sugar-production sector'.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p> CARICOM press release (May 11th 2005)</p><p>

<a href="http://www.harolddoan.com/modules.php?name=News&amp;file=article&amp;sid=2681" target="_self">http://www.harolddoan.com/modules.php?name=News&amp;file=article&amp;sid...</a> <br/> </p><p> Press report</p><p>

<a href="http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2005/05/18/sugar.shtml" target="_self">http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2005/05/18/sugar.shtml</a> <br/> </p><p> Press report ( <i>IPPmedia</i> 11/05/2005)</p><p>

<a href="http://www.ippmedia.com/ipp/financial/2005/05/11/39143.html" target="_self">http://www.ippmedia.com/ipp/financial/2005/05/11/39143.html</a> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> In the run up to the Hong Kong WTO Ministerial meeting the EC can expect to see intensified efforts to secure real and meaningful assistance in helping ACP sugar-exporting countries prepare for the impact of EU sugar-sector reform, since this lies at the heart of the issue of preference erosion. Should the EC be unable to make progress delivering on its policy commitments before Hong Kong, a growing number of ACP ministers may well question what ACP countries have to gain from the Doha Development Round.</p>
		</div>
		
